<section id="pointer-detection">
  <h2>Pointer Detection</h2>
  <p>Pointer detection is <strong>always on</strong> &mdash; no opt-in attribute needed. It uses CSS media queries to adapt interaction style to the device's input capabilities.</p>

  <code-block language="css" label="Pointer-aware rules (always active)">{{ pointerAware | escape }}</code-block>

  <h3>What It Does</h3>
  <dl>
    <dt><code>@media (pointer: coarse)</code></dt>
    <dd>Touch and stylus devices get 44px minimum target sizes on buttons, inputs, and selects &mdash; enforcing WCAG 2.5.8 target size requirements.</dd>

    <dt><code>@media (hover: none)</code></dt>
    <dd>On devices without hover (phones, tablets), hover-only motion effects like lift and scale are disabled. Content remains accessible without hover interactions.</dd>
  </dl>
</section>

<section id="with-themes">
  <h2>With Themes</h2>
  <p><code>data-fluid</code> composes with <code>data-theme</code>. Most themes only customize colors and fonts, so fluid scaling works without any theme-side changes.</p>
  <p>The <code>a11y-large-text</code> accessibility theme includes dedicated fluid compound rules &mdash; its larger base sizes (1.25rem body, 0.3125rem unit) also scale fluidly when <code>data-fluid</code> is present.</p>

  <code-block language="html" label="Fluid + theme composition">{{ '<html data-theme="ocean" data-fluid>\n<!-- Ocean colors + fluid type/spacing -->\n\n<html data-theme="a11y-large-text" data-fluid>\n<!-- Large text base + fluid scaling = maximum readability -->' | escape }}</code-block>
</section>

